  "slug": "wholemeal-scones",
  "title": "Wholemeal scones",
  "subtitle": "Nutty, hearty scones with a tender crumb",
  "excerpt": "Scones made with a mix of wholemeal and plain flour, giving a nuttier flavour and more substantial crumb than an all-white scone. Good with both sweet and savoury toppings.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Wholemeal scones are a British baking tradition documented in Florence White, Good Things in England (1932), Project Gutenberg, and in Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136, both of which record brown flour scone recipes. The use of a mix of wholemeal and white flour for a lighter crumb than all-wholemeal is standard modern British practice.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "About wholemeal scones",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A half-wholemeal, half-plain flour blend gives scones a noticeably nuttier flavour and slightly denser texture than all-white. The bran in the wholemeal flour shortens the gluten strands and gives the scone a more rustic, open crumb. These are excellent with mature cheese, or with jam and clotted cream where the wholemeal flavour works with the richness rather than against it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The rules for a good scone apply regardless of flour type: cold fat, minimal mixing, a hot oven, and eating them fresh. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "scone mix",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa9x7ns0000yov4pfmvag0f"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " can be made a few hours ahead up to the point of adding liquid; from there, mix, shape, and bake quickly.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ingredients",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
